Aaron Swartz was not a MIT student. From the MIT report:<p>&quot;Aaron Swartz was neither a member of the MIT staff, nor an enrolled student nor
alumnus, nor a member of the faculty. He was a regular visitor to the MIT campus and
interacted with MIT people and groups both on campus and off.&quot;

No, that statement <i>evaluates to</i> a pure value of type int.   In the process, it does something else as well that effects the visible behavior of the program.<p>The C equivalent of<p><pre><code>    putStrLn &quot;hello&quot;
</code></pre>
is probably actually<p><pre><code>    void putsHello(void) {
        puts(&quot;hello&quot;);
    }
</code></pre>
Unfortunately, function definitions aren&#x27;t something you can really manipulate at runtime in C.

C is &quot;pure&quot; too.<p>The statement<p><pre><code>   puts (&quot;hello&quot;);
</code></pre>
is a &quot;pure&quot; value of type int.
